Brazil  may cut about 60 billion reais
($32.1 billion) from its 2012 budget, more than previously
forecast, as it seeks to reach its primary budget surplus
target,  O Estado de S. Paulo  reported, citing unidentified
people at the  Finance Ministry .  The government had previously said it planned to cut 50
billion reais from this yearâ€™s budget, the Sao Paulo-based
newspaper reported. The government is aiming for a primary
budget surplus of 3.1 percent of gross domestic product in 2012,
